election_record.label: Massachusetts 1824 Electoral College

overview.note: "IMPORTANT HINT The Electoral Resolve of this State of June last, provides that each ballot shall contain fifteen names to be voted for as Electors of President and Vice President on Monday next. Some have suggested that unless fifteen names are given on the Ticket, the ballot will not be counted. To prevent any caviling, which is not anticipated, we respectfully suggest the expediency of substituting the name of another gentlemen of the same district in the place of one which may be stricken by any elector." The National Aegis (Worcester, MA). October 27, 1824.

"Votes - By law, the votes for Elector may be written or printed; but the legality of printed votes for Representative to Congress is doubted. Written votes are certainly legal." Columbian Centinel (Boston, MA). October 27, 1824.

"Printed Electoral Votes, in any quantity may be had at this office, for a trifling expense. Those towns which are not already supplied, will do well to make immediate application." Massachusetts Spy and Worcester Advertiser (Worcester, MA). October 27, 1824.
"Printed votes for Elector to President are allowable; this is not the case with printed votes for Representatives, they must be written." Newburyport Herald (Newburyport, MA). October 29, 1824.

The regular un-pledged (i.e. Crawford) ticket consisted of seven Republicans and eight Federalist. The Federal Party was still a viable force in Massachusetts and some of them decided to support a Crawford ticket composed entirely of Federal electors. This ticket replaced the Crawford Republican electors in Essex North, Middlesex, Worcester South, Hampden, Berkshire, Norfolk and Plymouth Districts. In the town of Worcester, another Federal Ticket, substituted Charles Jackson, Aaron Tufts and Ebenezer Gay for Samuel Towne, Jr., Edward H. Robbins and Thomas Hobart.
The name of the candidate from Worcester South has been given as Dr. Daniel Thacher, in the town of Weston, Daniel Shurber in town of Watertown, and Daniel Thurburn in town of Tisbury.
Massachusetts law required a vote for 15 separate electors in a statewide election. Votes were required for two at-large electors and one elector each from the state's 13 congressional districts.
